=============================================================================
@NODE DESCRIPTION "What is RexxOpt?"

                                 DESCRIPTION


ARexx  scripts  are  an  easy  way to adapt programs to your needs.  The only
problem with this is that ARexx is an interpreter language and due to this it
is  slow.   Some have tried to write compilers for ARexx, but those compilers
produce long (to be exact:  @{i}very @{ui}long) executables and that's what I dislike.
You  can't just change something in a compiled script because it is no more a
script  but  an executable.  You can use this as a kind of protection against
people  hacking around in your ARexx scripts but if you get such a script and
it doesn't work correctly on your system you have no chance to fix it.

Using  @{b}RexxOpt@{ub}  you  have  the possibility to speed up your scripts a lot and
still  are  able  to  change  them.  What @{b}RexxOpt@{ub} does is simply removing all
stuff  that is uneccessary for the script to be run.  This are comments which
slow  down  the  interpreter a lot, empty lines and unneccessary spaces/tabs.
Finally  the  whole  script  is  converted  to one single line containing all
commands.  This makes work with ARexx much more comfortable and faster.  Just
try it!

@ENDNODE
=============================================================================
@NODE REQUIREMENTS "What does RexxOpt need to work?"

                                REQUIREMENTS


You need AmigaOS 2.0+ to run @{b}RexxOpt@{ub}.

Additionally  it would be a good idea to have ARexx installed on your  system
since  it makes not much sense to  optimize ARexx scripts  when you can't use
them.

@ENDNODE
=============================================================================
@NODE INSTALLATION "How do I install RexxOpt?"

                                INSTALLATION


Installation is very simple.  Just copy the file @{b}RexxOpt@{ub} to somewhere on your
(hard-)disk. I think C: would be a good place. That's all.

@ENDNODE
=============================================================================
@NODE USAGE "How do I use RexxOpt?"

                                   USAGE


The usage of @{b}RexxOpt@{ub} is very easy. The syntax is as following:

    @{b}RexxOpt@{ub} <srcfile> <destfile> [COPYCOMMENTS] [SINGLESPACES] [RETAINLINES]
                                 [NOTITLECOMMENT] [SHOWNESTED] [NOSPACESTRIP]
                                 [KILLBLANKLINES]

@{b}RexxOpt@{ub} will  read <srcfile>, optimize it and  save the result to <destfile>.
(There  will  be  no  warning  if  <destfile>  already  exists,  it  will  be
overwritten, so be careful.)  All comments  will  be  removed, and  also  all
unneccessary empty  space characters  will be deleted.  The result is  a much
shorter and faster script, but a bit more confusing due to all commands being
put  into  one  single  line.  You may have problems in editing such a script
since  many editors aren't capable of handling extremely long lines like they
can  occur  here.   (On the other hand this is also a kind of protection ;-).
Consequently  it  is  advisable to keep the original script as you can easier
change  something  and  understand  the  scripts  when  there  are  comments.
Additionally  I  can't  guarantee  that @{b}RexxOpt@{ub}  will work with  every script
because  I  would  have to write a complete parser then and I think it is not
worth  the  effort  for  such  a small piece of code that started as a little
afternoon  hack.   Keeping the original is always a good idea in case @{b}RexxOpt@{ub}
fails.   (BTW:   If  you  find an ARexx script that fails to work after using
@{b}RexxOpt@{ub} please send it to me. Perhaps I can improve my code.)

Here are the options you can define:

COPYCOMMENTS    This will  prevent @{b}RexxOpt@{ub} from  removing the comments and so
                gain  less speed.  In former versions (< 1.4) of @{b}RexxOpt@{ub} this
                switch was needed when /* was used within strings, but due to
                the  quotation  check  introduced  with  V1.4  it  is  rather
                superflous.   Use  it  if  you  don't want any comments to be
                removed.

SINGLESPACES    Normally a  line like "filename = RESULT"  will cause @{b}RexxOpt@{ub}
                to  remove the spaces  and convert  this to "filename=RESULT"
                (provided it is not quoted).  If this leads to  problems  you
                can  specify  SINGLESPACES  to suppress  this  behaviour, the
                spaces  won't be removed then.  This option takes care of the
                following chars: + - ( ) , < > & * = / | % and ^. If you find
                a  case where this switch is needed please report it to me so
                that I can improve my code.

RETAINLINES     @{b}RexxOpt@{ub} won't put all commands into one single  line but will
                keep all  linefeeds so that you still have an easily readable
                file.

NOTITLECOMMENT  Normally  @{b}RexxOpt@{ub} inserts  a little comment in the first line
                of  the script which tells about the used version of @{b}RexxOpt@{ub}.
                It  is  neccessary for ARexx scripts to have a comment at the
                beginning  but  if  you  don't  want  that  use  this switch.
                Scripts  which  lack  a titlecomment won't be accepted by the
                ARexx  interpreter.   When  you use the NOTITLECOMMENT switch
                don't forget to add a comment at the beginning of the file.

SHOWNESTED      When this  is given @{b}RexxOpt@{ub} will report  every nested comment
                it  finds.   I  don't know if this is of use for anyone but I
                needed it for debugging purposes ;-).

NOSPACESTRIP    This prevents @{b}RexxOpt@{ub} from  replacing multiple spaces/tabs in
                a  row  by  one  single space/tab.  Most useful when you just
                want  to  strip  all  comments off your script by specifiying
                RETAINLINES and NOSPACESTRIP.

KILLBLANKLINES  This  removes any empty lines in the script and also prevents
                the  program   from  creating  any.  It  is  only  useful  in
                conjunction with RETAINLINES.

When  you  start  @{b}RexxOpt@{ub}  without any arguments  a little  help page will be
displayed.

If  anything  goes  wrong  @{b}RexxOpt@{ub}  will show you an @{"error message" LINK ERRORS} and abort.
Otherwise it shows how many bytes where gained by the optimization.

@ENDNODE
=============================================================================
@NODE ERRORS "What errors can happen?"

                                   ERRORS


When  an error occurs while @{b}RexxOpt@{ub} will give you an error message, free what
it allocated and then abort without saving anything.

The following error reports can happen:

@{i}"*** Comment termination without start in line xxx." @{ui}
     @{b}RexxOpt@{ub}  found  something  like  this:   SAY  "Hello"  */  and  this  is
     impossible  since  you  can't terminate a comment which you didn't start
     before.


@{i}"*** Comment not terminated." @{ui}
     This   occurs   when   there  where  more  comment  starts  ("/*")  than
     terminations ("*/") in the source file.  Try to specify @{"COPYCOMMENTS" LINK USAGE 31} in
     the  commandline  and  remove  the  comments  "by hand".  A script which
     provokes  this  error  to  happen  can  not  be run from ARexx since the
     interpreter also checks this and exits with an error.


@{i}"*** Destination file length: 0 bytes - nothing written." @{ui}
     This  happens  when  there's  nothing left after optimization.  Normally
     this  shouldn't  occur  because  this  means  that  that the source file
     doesn't do anything and a script that does nothing is senseless.


@{i}"*** Unmatched Quote" @{ui}
     This  occurs  when  a  quotation started and was not terminated.  Try to
     find  the  last  quotation  start (" or ') and check it.  A script which
     provokes  this  error  to  happen  can  not  be run from ARexx since the
     interpreter also checks this and exits with an error.


Some  other  errors  result  in  common  DOS  error messages which are rather
self-explaining.


@ENDNODE
=============================================================================
@NODE HISTORY "About the development of RexxOpt..."

                                  HISTORY


~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
1.5  (27.02.94) release

     - Forgot to remove spaces before/after % and ^. Fixed.
     - Problems with the  continuation character (,) fixed.  Thanks to Daniel
       J. Barrett for reporting this.

~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
1.4  (23.01.94) release

     - Improved space/tab stripping (didn't work with several spaces before
       an '=' character)
     - New switch: @{"NOSPACESTRIP" LINK USAGE 60}: Don't strip spaces.
     - Quotation check. From now on @{b}RexxOpt@{ub} won't change anything
       inside strings (starting/ending with ' or ")
     - New switch: @{"KILLBLANKLINES" LINK USAGE 65}: Kill empty lines.
     - No more problems with /* or */ inside quotes.
     - Spaces are now stripped before/after: + - ( ) , < > & ; * = / |
     - renamed EQUSPACES to @{"SINGLESPACES" LINK USAGE 37}, because of the above change

~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
1.3  (31.10.93) release

     - Spaces/tabs at the end of lines are removed now (not within comments)
     - Destination won't be written if file length is 0
     - Added a linefeed to titlecomment string
     - New switch: @{"SHOWNESTED" LINK USAGE 57}: Report nested comments
     - BUGFIX: Sometimes a comment termination wasn't removed
     - Byte gain is shown now
     - Improved error handling
     - Name of currently processed file is displayed now

~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
1.2  (05.09.93) release

     - New switch: @{"NOTITLECOMMENT" LINK USAGE 52}
     - BUGFIX: Didn't work correctly when a single "/" char was found within
       a comment

~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
1.1  (05.09.93)

     - New switch: @{"RETAINLINES" LINK USAGE 48}

~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
1.0  (28.08.93) release

     First release.

~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
@ENDNODE
